    <node id="1. Design group of Qualifications Wales is addressing issues regarding ensuring that the qualification is not too onerous from a teacher workload perspective, particularly in terms of assessment. This includes preventing unnecessary duplication of work for students.&#10;2. A stakeholder group and a practitioners group are working alongside the design group to test messages and gather feedback on the qualification's development from those who will be delivering it and potential employers.&#10;3. Professional learning opportunities are being created for teachers, both through regional consortia support and WJEC resources, as well as via the national approach to professional learning, with specific focus on addressing the professional learning needs of those already in the system.&#10;4. The design group is working to ensure greater consistency in delivery by understanding challenges and taking steps to address barriers for consistency." />
    <node id=" different way. And, as I said, it's quite a different departure from traditional O-levels, from GCSE-type subjects, where there is a programme of work and a syllabus. So, it is a different nature of qualification, and, therefore, as Andrew has just alluded to, schools have approached it in a different way. We are alert to that and Qualifications Wales, crucially, is alert to that, and we are looking to ensure greater consistency in how it is delivered in individual schools. We're also aware, in the school setting, in pre 16, there are some concerns about the onerousness of the workload associated with the evaluation of the students' work. Now, clearly, there is a difference between onerous and rigorous. We wrote the qualification to be a rigorous qualification for the students, but we don't want it to be jeopardised by the evaluation of it being too onerous. So, there's that balance to be struck. Again, that's one of the issues that the design group and Qualifications Wales are looking at. That process is a really important process, so there is the design group, but working alongside the design group, who they are testing the messages and testing their thoughts with, is a" />
    <node id=" really important process, so there is the design group, but working alongside the design group, who they are testing the messages and testing their thoughts with, is a stakeholder group, and there is also a practitioners group. So, that work by the design group is being tested with those people who have an interest: business, for instance, the world of work—is this qualification really giving students the skills that are valued by potential employers?—but it's also testing its thinking with the practitioners, those people who will be charged with the delivery of the qualification, and I think that's really important to be able to get an understanding of the challenges of making sure there's a consistency, and what are the barriers to that, and what steps need to be taken to ensure a greater level of consistency in delivery.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Is there a correlation between consistency in general? Because we know that there's polarisation in the secondary school sector between the good schools and the not-so-good schools. And is there a correlation between—if the schools are good according to Estyn, or excellent, are they also good, excellent at delivering the bac? Is it a fundamental inconsistency across the sector that's causing" />
    <node id="1. Flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate: The Welsh Baccalaureate offers flexibility to students by providing different levels (Foundation, National, and Advanced) and pathways (Core, Creative, Enterprise and Commerce, Global Citizenship, and Health and Social Care) based on their interests and career goals. This flexibility allows students to tailor the qualification to their needs and choose subjects that they are passionate about, which can positively influence their perception and value of the program.&#10;&#10;2. Recognition by Russell Group universities: The Welsh Baccalaureate is recognized by many Russell Group universities as equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that may lower offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This recognition increases the value and prestige of the qualification among learners, particularly those who aspire to attend these competitive institutions. Knowing that the Welsh Baccalaureate can help them meet university entrance requirements encourages more students to consider taking it, improving its perception and value at key stage 4 and post-16.&#10;&#10;3. Influence of school leadership: The support and promotion of the Welsh Baccalaureate by school leaders play a significant role in shaping learners' perceptions and valuation of the qualification. When school leaders actively encourage students to participate in the program, create an environment that values and supports its successful completion, and communicate its benefits clearly, learners are more likely to view the Welsh Baccalaureate as a valuable and meaningful educational experience.&#10;&#10;In summary, the flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate, its recognition by Russell Group universities, and the influence of school leadership contribute to its value and perception among learners at key stage 4 or post-16. The qualification's adaptability allows students to personalize their learning experience, while university recognition increases its prestige. Positive endorsement and support from school leaders further enhance learners' perceptions and motivation to engage with the Welsh Baccalaureate." />
    <node id="1. Introducing a grading system for the Welsh Baccalaureate addresses concerns about its lack of rigor by providing a means of measuring and differentiating students' performance, thereby ensuring that the qualification is taken seriously and valued in its own right. This also enables universities and employers to better assess the achievements of Welsh Baccalaureate students when making offers or recruitment decisions.&#10;2. An independent process benchmarking qualifications helps to establish the credibility and rigor of the Welsh Baccalaureate by comparing it with other qualifications, both within Wales and internationally. This provides assurance that the Welsh Baccalaureate meets appropriate standards and is recognized as a valuable and rigorous qualification, thus enhancing its value and addressing concerns about its perceived lack of rigor.&#10;3. By having a grading system and independent benchmarking process in place, the Welsh Baccalaureate can be more consistently valued and understood by universities and employers across the UK. This ensures that Welsh students are not disadvantaged when applying for further education or jobs, as their qualifications will be recognized and appreciated for their rigor and value.&#10;4. The combination of a grading system and independent benchmarking process can help to dispel negative perceptions about the Welsh Baccalaureate, such as claims that it lacks rigor, is passively marked, or has grades that are inflated. By demonstrating the credibility and value of the qualification, these concerns can be addressed, and the Welsh Baccalaureate can be seen as a genuinely rigorous and valuable educational experience for students in Wales." />
    <node id="1. The design group of Qualifications Wales is addressing issues regarding ensuring that the new qualification is not too onerous from a teacher workload perspective, particularly in terms of assessment. This includes preventing unnecessary duplication of work for students. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 1)&#10;2. Specific resources and professional learning programs are being made available for teachers to ensure they have the skills and confidence to deliver the new qualification in a high-quality manner. This is in line with past practice of providing resources when introducing reformed qualifications. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 1-2)&#10;3. There will be opportunities via regional consortia for support in teaching the qualification, and the WJEC has resources and support available. As part of the national approach to professional learning, there will be specific focus on addressing the professional learning needs of those already in the system. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 3)&#10;4. ITE reforms are primarily aimed at preparing teachers for 'Successful Futures' and delivering the Welsh baccalaureate with the required pedagogical principles. Ensuring teachers have these skills is a part of the accreditation process for new ITE providers. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 4)&#10;5. The design group will continue to refine the qualification and ensure consistency in delivery by understanding challenges and taking steps to address barriers for consistency. (implied throughout Kirsty Williams AM's statements)" />
    <node id=" professional learning needs of those already in the system are addressed. Of course, our accreditation for our new initial teacher education is predominantly addressed at being able to deliver the new curriculum, but, if you think about the elements of 'Successful Futures' and the skills and the knowledge and the pedagogy associated with that, it's very much in line with the Welsh baccalaureate challenge certificate. So, actually, there are opportunities via initial teacher education as well, and we continue to need to look to work with our partners to be able to reinforce why this is a worthwhile qualification. And I have to say I think the best people to do that—. It's not me. I'd like to see past students of the Welsh baccalaureate being able to talk about their own experiences and why it's made a difference to them. I come across individuals for whom their place at university has been secured by that Welsh baccalaureate, and, all of a sudden, if that's what's got you your place, it becomes a lot more valuable than perhaps it was six months before. We need to make sure that students are aware, and teachers and school leaders are aware, of the importance that this qualification has.&#10;" />
    <node id="&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. The next questions are from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: This is about the wider impact of studying the Welsh bac on other curriculum subjects and education provision, and we've had representations in that it is causing some concerns. So, do you have any concerns about the effect that the Welsh bac may be having on wider education provisions, such as the narrowing of the curriculum at key stage 4?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: No. Obviously, schools are responsible for planning their local curriculum offer, and that needs to meet the needs of their learners, and it also needs to meet the needs of the Learning and Skills (Wales) Measure 2009. So, there should be a wide variety of choices available. I believe that the skills challenge certificate actually does ensure that there is a broad curriculum and that children are exposed to different learning opportunities. And so, rather than narrowing it, I believe the Welsh bac helps us to make sure that there is an expansive curriculum, and that lots of different issues are explored in the skills challenge certificate that ensure not just academic skills are developed, but," />
    <node id="1. Pathways and Levels: The Welsh Baccalaureate offers various pathways and levels (Foundation, National, and Advanced), which can lead to inconsistencies in how the qualification is provided. Different pathways and levels may have varying expectations, assessment methods, and challenges, impacting learners' perception and understanding of its value.&#10;&#10;2. School Leadership: The way school leaders perceive and support the Welsh Baccalaureate has a significant influence on how it is provided in their institutions. If school leaders do not value or understand the qualification, they may not provide adequate resources, training, or recognition for students undertaking it, negatively impacting learners' perception of its value.&#10;&#10;3. Teacher Training and Resources: Inconsistent teacher training and resources can also contribute to variability in the provision of the Welsh Baccalaureate. If teachers are not properly trained or have limited access to high-quality resources, they may struggle to deliver the program effectively, leading to inconsistencies in how it is experienced by learners.&#10;&#10;4. Workload and Well-being: Concerns about workload and well-being associated with the Welsh Baccalaureate can impact its provision and learners' perception of its value. If students feel overwhelmed by the demands of the qualification, they may perceive it as less valuable or desirable. Similarly, if teachers find it challenging to balance the Welsh Baccalaureate with other qualifications, they may not provide the same level of support and commitment to the program.&#10;&#10;5. Recognition by Universities and Employers: The inconsistency in how universities and employers value the Welsh Baccalaureate can impact learners' perception of its worth. If some institutions do not recognize or value the qualification as highly as others, students may feel less motivated to undertake it or perceive it as less beneficial for their future prospects.&#10;&#10;In summary, various factors contribute to the inconsistency in how the Welsh Baccalaureate is provided, including pathways and levels, school leadership, teacher training and resources, workload and well-being, and recognition by universities and employers. These inconsistencies can impact learners' perception and understanding of the qualification's value, potentially leading to misunderstandings or undervaluation of its benefits." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh baccalaureate is valued by many universities, including Russell Group universities, as an equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that can lower offer requirements when passed at a certain level. This indicates that the qualification is recognized for its rigor and relevance to undergraduate studies.&#10;2. The skills developed through the Welsh baccalaureate, such as project management, research, and independent learning, are seen as beneficial for the transition from A-level work to university-type work. This suggests that students who have engaged in this type of qualification may be better prepared for the demands of undergraduate studies.&#10;3. There is also evidence to suggest that these skills can be valuable in gaining work experience and internships, as they are highly valued by employers. This means that students who have completed project-based, individual-led, research-based work such as the Welsh baccalaureate or EPQ may have an advantage when it comes to securing work experience and internships during their undergraduate studies.&#10;4. Overall, there is a positive correlation between students who have engaged in project-based, individual-led, research-based work such as the Welsh baccalaureate and EPQ qualifications in the UK, and their potential success in undergraduate studies and gaining work experience." />
    <node id=" who have been involved in project-based work—and, of course, that's not just the Welsh baccalaureate, that would be the EPQ, which is a qualification that is rapidly gaining traction in England. That is an extended project—research based—qualification, very similar to the individual project element of the Welsh baccalaureate. The EPQ in England is seen as a qualification taken by more able and talented students, and what we see in some of the research that is coming forward is that those students who have engaged in that type of work, project-based work, individual-led, research-based work—those skills are the skills that are really attuned to the nature of university-type work. Therefore, that is valued by universities and there is some indication to say that there is a correlation between the students who have undertaken that work and their potential success at undergraduate level. They also tell me that there is a link between, for instance, being able then to use those skills to gain work experience, placements and internships in the private sector and in the world of work, because, as I said, those types of skills are really, really valuable and therefore that's why they value the qualification.&#10;Spe" />
    <node id="ac?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I think sometimes colleges make the decision that four or five A-levels is of an advantage, and therefore, if you're asking students to carry that workload, which is a considerable workload, that's the preferred route for more able and talented students. Again, what is quite clear in all the conversations that I have had with Russell Group universities, including Oxford and Cambridge, is that this is a myth. What universities tell me they want is not necessarily students with four or five A-levels; they want students with three really exceptional grades at A-level and a Welsh baccalaureate. I think that's really, really an important message to get across—that it is not necessary to do four or five A-levels if you aspire to go to these Russell Group universities, or if you decide you want to apply to Oxford and Cambridge. As I said, in the conversations that we have had—and there is actually some research, and I will let the committee have links to the research. There is some research to suggest that those students who have been involved in project-based work—and, of course, that's not just the Welsh baccalaureate, that would be the EP" />
    <node id="1. The recommended approach to address the inconsistency in how institutions and universities across the UK make admissions offers regarding the skills challenge certificate is not explicitly stated in the transcripts. However, Kirsty Williams AM suggests that it's important for Qualifications Wales to ensure that universities understand the value of Welsh qualifications, including the Welsh baccalaureate. This will become increasingly crucial as English and Welsh qualifications diverge.&#10;2. The discussion also highlights the varying perspectives on the Welsh baccalaureate, with some universities considering it less valuable when it was a 'yes'/'no' qualification. Since September 2015, the skills challenge certificate has been a graded qualification, which has led to an improvement in how some universities regard it.&#10;3. To address inconsistencies, there could be continued efforts to reach out to universities and emphasize the value of the Welsh baccalaureate, as well as encouraging more open communication between Qualifications Wales and higher education institutions. Additionally, ongoing research and surveys can help in understanding university practices better and addressing any potential disadvantages faced by Welsh students with the skills challenge certificate." />
    <node id="Content: Yes, and it's representing the evidence that we received.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And I'm presenting you with the evidence that I've received.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: But it will be presented to you as a submission from this committee, no doubt. Let's look at some admissions offers instead then. You do concede that there is inconsistency with how admissions offers are made with regard to the skills challenge certificate. How would you suggest that that is addressed?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Hefin, each individual institution and university the length and breadth of the UK have different ways in which they make offers to individuals. What is absolutely clear to me, and if the concern is around the type of institution—. So, for instance, it is accepted as a third-grade offer in Bristol, Edinburgh, Exeter, Lancaster, Leeds, Leicester, Liverpool, the London School of Economics—some of the highest performing universities and Russell Group universities. It is accepted as a fourth qualification or amends the offer in places like Bath University, and it is accepted in tariff-point offers in places like Hull and the University of the West of England. So there is" />
