    <node id="The Cabinet Secretary for Education, Kirsty Williams AM, values the Welsh Baccalaureate highly and believes it contributes to a broad and balanced curriculum that prepares young people for further study and work. She has consistently received support from universities across the United Kingdom, who view the qualification as valuable and not disadvantageous to Welsh students. Williams emphasizes the importance of ensuring that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand the value and significance of the Welsh Baccalaureate for future success." />
    <node id="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee. We've received no apologies for absence. Can I ask Members whether there are any declarations of interest, please? No. Okay. Thank you. Item 2 this morning is our evidence session with the Cabinet Secretary for Education for our inquiry into the status of the Welsh baccalaureate qualification. I'm very pleased to welcome Kirsty Williams AM, Cabinet Secretary for Education; Kevin Palmer, who is deputy director, pedagogy, leadership and professional learning; and Andrew Clark, deputy director, further education and apprenticeships division. So, thank you all for attending, and we're looking forward to hearing what you've got to say. If you're happy, Cabinet Secretary, we'll go straight to questions.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: And the first questions are from Julie Morgan.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Thank you very much, Chair, and bore da. I was going to ask some general questions about the value of the baccalaureate. Could you give us your views on how the" />
    <node id="1. The varying opinions regarding the rigor and equivalency of the Skills Challenge Certificate compared to traditional A-level qualifications can be attributed to differences in understanding and implementation of the Welsh Baccalaureate across schools. Some teachers may not be taking the bac as seriously as others, which could lead to inconsistencies in how the qualification is perceived by universities and students.&#10;2. Kirsty Williams AM emphasizes that the Skills Challenge Certificate should not be held up as equivalent to an A-level, but rather viewed as a qualification that develops different skills. It is important to acknowledge these differences and understand that the Welsh Baccalaureate contributes to a broad and balanced curriculum, exposing students to various learning opportunities and helping them develop a wider range of knowledge and skills.&#10;3. To uphold the ethos and skills associated with these qualifications in schools, there should be continued efforts to ensure that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand the value and significance of the Welsh Baccalaureate for future success. Strengthening and clarifying guidance for school leaders regarding decision-making on whether a qualification is suitable for students can help maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities.&#10;4. Ongoing research, surveys, and open communication between Qualifications Wales and higher education institutions can help address any potential disadvantages faced by Welsh students with the Skills Challenge Certificate, ensuring that institutions across the UK understand its value as Welsh qualifications diverge from English ones." />
