    <node id="1. The advanced level Welsh Baccalaureate is equivalent to an A-level in rigor, as it has been benchmarked against A-levels and assigned a UCAS tariff. It is used by universities for admission purposes similarly to how they use A-level qualifications. The individual project work required by the Welsh Baccalaureate is valued by universities because it teaches a different set of skills compared to traditional syllabi, demanding more from individual students and encouraging independent learning.&#10;&#10;2. There has been some confusion regarding the rigor and equivalency of the Skills Challenge Certificate within the Welsh Baccalaureate, which can be attributed to differences in implementation across schools. Some teachers may not take the bac as seriously as others, leading to inconsistencies in how the qualification is perceived by universities and students.&#10;&#10;3. Kirsty Williams AM clarifies that the Skills Challenge Certificate should not be considered equivalent to an A-level but rather a valuable qualification that develops different skills. It contributes to a broad and balanced curriculum, providing students with diverse learning opportunities and helping them build various knowledge areas and skillsets.&#10;&#10;4. To maintain the ethos of these qualifications in schools, it is crucial to ensure that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand the value and significance of the Welsh Baccalaureate for future success. Strengthening guidance for school leaders on deciding whether a qualification is suitable for their students can help preserve positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities.&#10;&#10;5. Ongoing research, surveys, and open communication between Qualifications Wales and higher education institutions will help address any potential disadvantages faced by Welsh students with the Skills Challenge Certificate, ensuring that institutions across the UK understand its value as Welsh qualifications diverge from English ones." />
    <node id="; there is an independent process that benchmarks qualifications. The fact is that at advanced level—because I don't know if you're making these observations about the pre-16 Welsh bac, or whether we're talking about the advanced level qualification—that is the equivalent of an A-level. It's been benchmarked against A-levels. It has a UCAS tariff associated with it. It is used by universities as a means of qualification that gains entrance into a university in just the same way as an A-level is. So, therefore, I don't have any concerns about the rigour of the qualification. In terms of spoon-feeding, one of the reasons why universities like the qualification is that it's very difficult, for instance, in the individual project work to be spoon-fed. It is very demanding of individual students, and it's very difficult in a way. That's one of the reasons why it's valuable, isn't it, because it teaches a different set of skills? Because if you're doing a traditional, say, history A-level or a science A-level, there's a very strict syllabus and a course, there's a textbook and people are taught to that particular syllabus; with the Welsh bac, it" />
    <node id="1. ITE reforms: The accreditation process for ITE programs now includes a criterion that requires teachers to help students make connections across their learning, focusing on important topics such as citizenship, enterprise, financial capability, and sustainability. This change is intended to prepare teachers to effectively deliver the Welsh Baccalaureate and other connected learning experiences.&#10;&#10;2. Professional learning: The Welsh Government emphasizes the importance of professional learning for in-service teachers to ensure they have the necessary skills and confidence to teach the Welsh Baccalaureate effectively. This is addressed through funding allocated to consortia, which then distribute it to individual schools based on their specific professional learning needs, including the ability to deliver the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;&#10;3. Curriculum alignment: The new curriculum in ITE programs focuses on elements of 'Successful Futures', which are closely aligned with the skills and knowledge required for the Welsh Baccalaureate Challenge Certificate. This overlap provides opportunities to reinforce the value of the Welsh Baccalaureate within initial teacher education, emphasizing its importance to students, teachers, and school leaders.&#10;&#10;4. Strengthening guidance: In response to concerns from teachers who feel undermined by parents' calls to the Welsh Government, there is a plan to strengthen and clarify guidance for school leaders regarding decision-making on suitable qualifications for students. This step aims to ensure consistency in approach, prevent confusion, and maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities." />
    <node id=" teacher learning from Suzy.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Actually, I've asked the question that I wanted to ask.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, you don't want to—&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: By all means you ask the others I had.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. You have referred to training already. The committee's got two concerns, really. One is about preparedness in ITE to teach the Welsh bac, so I don't know if you want to expand on how teachers are being skilled up at that level to deliver the Welsh bac effectively.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: In the accreditation process, which has not been without its pain, and some significant decisions made in that regard, the criteria for the ITE programmes note that, and I'm going to quote it: 'Teachers should be able to help children and young people to make links across their learning, bringing together different aspects to examine, for example, important topics such as citizenship, enterprise, financial capability and sustainability.' So, the prime driver for our ITE reforms, obviously, is the preparedness for" />
    <node id="1. The decision of some FE colleges to exempt their highest performing students from completing the Welsh Baccalaureate might be driven by concerns that these students may not be meeting expectations for those with three A-levels. This could be based on perceptions that the Baccalaureate is less academically rigorous or relevant compared to traditional A-level subjects.&#10;2. There might also be suspicions that the Welsh Baccalaureate could potentially distract high-achieving students from focusing on their core academic subjects, which are often prioritized by universities and employers. This concern may stem from a lack of understanding about the value and recognition of the Baccalaureate among certain educational institutions and stakeholders.&#10;3. To address these concerns, it would be helpful to gather more information about the specific reasons FE colleges are exempting their highest performing students from the Welsh Baccalaureate. This could involve conducting surveys or interviews with college administrators, teachers, and students to better understand their perspectives and experiences.&#10;4. It may also be beneficial for education authorities to provide additional guidance and support for FE colleges regarding the suitability and benefits of the Welsh Baccalaureate for high-achieving students. This could involve sharing research on the academic outcomes and skill development associated with the Baccalaureate, as well as best practices from colleges that have successfully integrated it into their curriculum for top-performing students.&#10;5. Ultimately, addressing the concerns of FE colleges about the Welsh Baccalaureate will require a collaborative effort between education authorities, teachers, parents, and students to ensure that all parties understand the value and significance of the qualification for future success. This may involve ongoing communication, professional development opportunities, and resources to support the implementation and integration of the Baccalaureate into FE college curricula." />
    <node id="The significant change made to the Skills Challenge Certificate in 2015 was that it shifted from a 'yes'/'no' qualification to a graded one. This change has led to an improvement in how some universities regard it, as they previously held it in less regard when it was not a graded qualification. The new grading system has resulted in more universities recognizing the value of the Skills Challenge Certificate and considering it useful for developing a specific set of skills that help students transition into higher education. This shift has contributed to ensuring that Welsh students undertaking this qualification are not at any detriment, and it is valued by Russell Group universities and others across the UK." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh government plans to ensure consistent support and enthusiasm for the Welsh Baccalaureate (the &quot;bac&quot;) from leaders by addressing concerns about teacher workload. A design group of Qualifications Wales is working on ensuring that the qualification is not too burdensome in terms of assessment, aiming to prevent unnecessary duplication of work for both teachers and students.&#10;2. They will provide specific resources and professional learning programs for teachers to ensure they have the necessary skills and confidence to deliver the new qualification effectively. This initiative aligns with past practices of offering support when introducing reformed qualifications.&#10;3. Opportunities for regional consortia support and WJEC resources will be available, as well as a national approach to professional learning focused on addressing the professional learning needs of those already in the system.&#10;4. The government is also reforming Initial Teacher Education (ITE) to prepare teachers for 'Successful Futures' and delivering the Welsh baccalaureate with the required pedagogical principles. Ensuring teachers have these skills is part of the accreditation process for new ITE providers.&#10;5. By addressing these concerns and creating an enabling environment through professional learning opportunities, the Welsh government aims to foster consistency in delivering the qualification and maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities." />
    <node id="1. Perception of Less Academic Rigor: FE colleges may perceive the Welsh Baccalaureate as less academically rigorous or relevant compared to traditional A-level subjects, leading them to exempt high-achieving students from completing it. This could be due to a lack of understanding about the value and recognition of the Baccalaureate among certain educational institutions and stakeholders.&#10;2. Focus on Core Academic Subjects: FE colleges might worry that the Welsh Baccalaureate could distract high-achieving students from focusing on their core academic subjects, which are often prioritized by universities and employers. These colleges may believe that having four or five A-levels would provide a more substantial foundation for future studies or careers.&#10;3. Lack of Information: There might be a lack of information about the specific reasons FE colleges are exempting their highest performing students from the Welsh Baccalaureate. Gathering more information through surveys, interviews, and research could help address these concerns and provide a clearer understanding of the perspectives and experiences of college administrators, teachers, and students.&#10;4. Guidance and Support: Education authorities can play a role in addressing these concerns by providing additional guidance and support for FE colleges regarding the suitability and benefits of the Welsh Baccalaureate for high-achieving students. Sharing research on academic outcomes and skill development associated with the Baccalaureate, as well as best practices from successful colleges, could help integrate it into curricula for top-performing students.&#10;&#10;In summary, FE colleges may be exempting their highest performing students from the Welsh Baccalaureate due to concerns about academic rigor and relevance, a potential distraction from core subjects, or a lack of information on the benefits of the qualification. Addressing these concerns requires collaboration between education authorities, teachers, parents, and students, as well as ongoing communication, professional development opportunities, and resources to support the implementation and integration of the Baccalaureate into FE college curricula." />
    <node id="1. The universities in Wales are reluctant to participate in the committee's work or submit evidence regarding the Welsh baccalaureate possibly due to several reasons:&#10;   - They may not want to be drawn into the argument between the Government and the committee, as suggested by Sian Gwenllian AM. This reluctance could indicate a desire to remain neutral in political disputes.&#10;   - Universities Wales, which represents the interests of universities in Wales, might prefer to address this matter through their own channels or maintain a unified position on behalf of their member institutions.&#10;   - There could be concerns about potential repercussions for engaging in a public disagreement with the Government or the committee, which may lead universities to avoid participation.&#10;&#10;2. The absence of Welsh universities in the committee's work might not necessarily signify that they do not want to be involved in the disagreement between the Government and the committee. However, their reluctance could be interpreted as a desire to maintain a professional distance from political debates or an attempt to avoid being associated with any controversy. It is also possible that universities may perceive their involvement as unnecessary, given that the Cabinet Secretary, Kirsty Williams AM, has stated that she consistently receives support from UK universities regarding the Welsh baccalaureate's value." />
    <node id="1. Ensuring there is support in schools: Kirsty Williams acknowledges that studying A-levels can be a stressful time for young people and emphasizes the need to provide support within schools. This includes ensuring students make informed choices about their qualifications, understanding the importance of quality over quantity in their work, and receiving good information, advice, and guidance from teachers and advisors.&#10;2. Promoting the Welsh Baccalaureate: Kirsty Williams values the Welsh Baccalaureate as contributing to a broad and balanced curriculum that prepares young people for further study and work. She highlights that universities across the UK view the qualification positively, ensuring school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand its value and significance for future success.&#10;3. Flexibility in decision-making: Julie Morgan raises concerns about some teachers feeling undermined when insisting on pupils doing certain qualifications, while facing pressure from parents. She suggests strengthening and clarifying the guidance for school leaders regarding decision-making on suitable qualifications to maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities. This would ensure consistency in approach and prevent confusion.&#10;4. Addressing concerns about well-being: Kirsty Williams acknowledges that there are concerns about how some students balance the Welsh Bac with other qualifications, workload issues associated with it, and its potential impact on their well-being. To address these concerns, Qualifications Wales has undertaken a review to refine the Welsh baccalaureate and ensure that taking the qualification is the norm for students while being flexible to protect students' well-being when necessary.&#10;&#10;In summary, measures being put in place to help young people deal with added pressures and stress include providing support within schools, promoting high-value qualifications like the Welsh Baccalaureate, ensuring consistent decision-making on suitable qualifications, and addressing concerns related to well-being and workload." />
    <node id=" As you know, mental health and the emotional health of our children and young people is a very core issue for this committee, and Estyn have said that studying the skills challenge certificate alongside three or four A-levels is a significant factor in causing stress for some young people. How do you respond to that?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, I would be the first to acknowledge that studying A-levels can be a very stressful time. That's because students, rightly, regard those qualifications as high stakes and as having a profound effect on the opportunities for the rest of their lives. So, the mere fact of studying A-levels can be a really stressful time for students because they understand how important they are, and students want to do well and they want to be able to move on to the next stage, either of work or of university. We also know—and Estyn reflects this—that students are also often trying to combine that with part-time jobs. These students are of an age when they want to be out and about and earning some of their own money and being a bit more independent. So, that adds added pressure to them. So, undoubtedly, this is a stressful time in young people's lives and we" />
    <node id=" and being a bit more independent. So, that adds added pressure to them. So, undoubtedly, this is a stressful time in young people's lives and we need to ensure that there is support in school to support young people through this time to make sure that students are making the right choices in terms of their A-levels and the qualifications that they're doing so they're not having to do more because they're under the impression that, by doing more, that's going to make them more likely to succeed. What we know, actually, is it's about the quality of what you do rather than the entirety of what you do that's important to universities, and we need to make sure that students are getting really good information, advice and guidance and support at what is a challenging time in their lives, because, of course, it comes on top of working really hard for your GCSEs and then you have, the following year, AS-level examinations and A-level examinations after that. So, these are stressful times in children's lives and they realise the importance of these as high-stakes qualifications.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. The next questions are from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker:" />
    <node id=", in some cases, there needs to be flexibility to ensure that the well-being of the student is not compromised.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: And so would you say that it's valued by learners more or less at key stage 4 or post 16?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, I think that, as I said, the vast majority of students I meet report very positively about the opportunities that are afforded for studying at that level. Occasionally, we hear from students who I believe think that in studying the subject they may be compromising their chances because they want to do additional A-levels, and I'm sure we'll come on to, later on, whether universities, and whether the Russell Group universities in particular, value the qualification. But I feel that there are particular strengths. And I think what's really important, and, in talking to universities, since the qualification became graded, rather than just a pass/fail qualification—I think that added rigour since 2015 has been particularly important in ensuring that there's real value in students undertaking that work.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: And what about the effect that the leadership in the school has on the way that the bac is received?" />
    <node id="1. The importance and high stakes associated with A-level qualifications: Kirsty Williams AM recognizes that the pressure to perform well in A-levels can be a significant source of stress for students, as they understand the profound impact these qualifications have on their future opportunities for work or university education.&#10;&#10;2. Combining studies with part-time jobs: Many students trying to balance A-levels with part-time jobs experience added pressure and stress. This is especially true for young people who want to be financially independent and earn their own money.&#10;&#10;3. Desire for social activities and independence: The committee mentioned that this stage of life is a time when young people want to be out and about, which can contribute to the stress they experience during their A-level studies. Kirsty Williams AM acknowledges this need for social interaction and independence among students.&#10;&#10;4. Inadequate understanding and implementation of the Welsh Baccalaureate: While not directly stated in the transcript, it is implied that inconsistencies in how the Welsh Baccalaureate (including the Skills Challenge Certificate) is perceived and implemented across schools may exacerbate students' stress levels. Ensuring that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand its value and significance can help alleviate some of this pressure." />
    <node id="1. The question asks whether there are plans to pause the universal roll-out of the Welsh Baccalaureate, considering that not all schools are currently ready to deliver it to a high standard. From the transcript, it is clear that Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, does not intend to pause the roll-out. She emphasizes the importance of investing in professional learning to ensure that all schools can deliver the qualification well, rather than stopping the opportunity for students to study it." />
    <node id=" student. But when I talk about universal adoption, I expect all our institutions to be in a position to deliver the qualification, and I believe it should be an entitlement for Welsh students to be able to undertake this qualification.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: But not an obligation—that's the bit I'm trying to get at.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I think it should become the norm, and if there are exceptions to that, and there could well be for very legitimate reasons, I think that that flexibility should be allowed. But I think, for those students who are not doing that Welsh baccalaureate, there should be evidence as to why that decision has been taken.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay, so there's a presumption. I think the performance measures, probably, are likely to sharpen the minds of some school leaders, so I won't pursue that. But can you tell me what lesson you may have learnt from the universal obligation for students to study Welsh language in schools when those schools weren't particularly ready to offer a quality course?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: As we've rehearsed ear" />
    <node id="1. By &quot;universal adoption&quot; of the Welsh Baccalaureate, Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, means that all institutions should be in a position to deliver the qualification. She believes it should be an entitlement for all Welsh students to have access to and study this qualification, with the aim of it becoming the norm for students to take the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;2. While emphasizing the importance of universal adoption, Kirsty Williams AM also recognizes exceptions to the alignment of the Welsh Baccalaureate with individual students' well-being. She acknowledges that there may be specific cases where taking the Welsh Baccalaureate might not be suitable for a student due to valid reasons related to their well-being. In such situations, she believes flexibility should be allowed, and there should be evidence justifying why the decision was taken for the student not to pursue the qualification." />
    <node id="Content: Okay, thanks. Thank you, Chair.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Actually, it's your set of questions next on universal adoption.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: I'll try and keep this on the shorter side, if that's okay, everybody. You say in your evidence that you expect universal adoption, basically, by 2020, I think it is, or it might be 2019. What do you think universal adoption actually means? What does it look like? Does it mean 100 per cent adoption?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: What is means is that I expect all institutions to be in a position to deliver the Welsh baccalaureate. I believe it should be an entitlement to all Welsh students to be able to study this qualification, and I believe we should work to the situation where it becomes the norm to take the Welsh baccalaureate. I also recognise that in some individual cases, there may be very good reasons why perhaps this is not aligned to the well-being of that particular student. But when I talk about universal adoption, I expect all our institutions to be in a position to deliver the qualification, and I believe it should be an" />
    <node id="1. The launch of the first Welsh-medium MOOC (Massive Open Online Course) by the University of Bath and Aberystwyth University is significant as it demonstrates a strong commitment from these universities to support the Welsh baccalaureate qualification. This resource will help students develop skills in choosing a thesis, conducting independent research, and proper referencing for their individual project component.&#10;2. The response to this MOOC has been positive, with over 1,000 students signing up for it so far. This indicates that there is considerable interest among Welsh baccalaureate students in utilizing such resources to strengthen their skills and improve their projects.&#10;&#10;The first Welsh-medium MOOC is an important development as it shows the Universities of Bath and Aberystwyth's dedication to the Welsh baccalaureate, with over 1,000 students already taking advantage of this valuable resource." />
    <node id=", it is an online—a massive open online course. So, it's a course that is delivered free of charge, and it's delivered by information technology. So, the University of Bath have done this MOOC to support students with the EPQ. They have just launched, in conjunction with Aberystwyth University, a bilingual MOOC for the individual project for Welsh bac. It's our understanding it is the first ever Welsh-medium MOOC, we think; we're not aware of any others. And this resource is there for students to give them advice on how they do choose the thesis for their individual project: how do you go about, then, undertaking good independent research; how do you reference properly, to ensure that you do that correctly? And we've seen over 1,000 students already sign up for the MOOC. So, increasingly, there are lots and lots of new resources out there for both teachers and students to make the most of. And the fact that Bath and Aberystwyth have worked together on this, I believe, shows their commitment and a demonstration of their support for this qualification, otherwise why would the University of Bath bother, if they weren't interested in it?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle" />
    <node id="1. Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, is reluctant to confirm whether young people are leaving Wales to avoid the Welsh Baccalaureate (Welsh bac) qualification because she believes there could be a variety of reasons why students make that decision. She mentions that it might be easier to attribute the choice to the Welsh Baccalaureate, but in reality, there could be other factors at play. This reluctance stems from her desire to avoid oversimplifying students' motivations and to encourage a more comprehensive understanding of their choices." />
    <node id="wenllian AM&#10;Content: The evidence that we've had from one of the teaching unions—robust and clear evidence—is that this is happening, that is, that young people are leaving Wales to go over the border to schools in England in order to avoid the Welsh bac. That's exactly what was said to us. But you don't accept that evidence.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I'm not saying that I don't accept it. I'm saying that I think there are a wide variety of reasons why students make decisions about where to study. I'm not aware of any comprehensive piece of work that has looked at those motivations, and I think there could be a whole host of reasons why children are deciding to move across the border. Perhaps the Welsh bac is an easy one to place that hook on, and that's easier to acknowledge, isn't it, than saying that perhaps students are making that choice for other reasons.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. The next questions, then, are on teacher learning from Suzy.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Actually, I've asked the question that I wanted to ask.&#10;Spe" />
    <node id=" is to schools and colleges?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Very happy to do that. As I said, from time to time, parents do indeed contact Welsh Government, and in that contact there is a whole variety of reasons why that parent feels the Welsh baccalaureate is not in the best interests of those children. Sometimes, that can go from the extreme of, 'I want my child to do five A-levels and I think that's in their best interest to get into Oxford and Cambridge'—I would argue that that is a myth, around the need to do that many A-levels—through to, 'Actually, my child has a range of learning needs, and actually this qualification isn't suited to them. Making them go out and do voluntary work in an organisation with people that don't understand their needs and they are unfamiliar with could jeopardise my child's ability and my child's well-being.' So, there's a whole range of reasons why sometimes people have concerns about the Welsh baccalaureate. Some of those are very legitimate concerns. Sometimes, they're based on information that, perhaps, isn't correct, or the myths around, 'I need to do five A-levels if" />
    <node id="1. The design group of Qualifications Wales is addressing issues regarding ensuring that the new qualification is not too onerous from a teacher workload perspective, particularly in terms of assessment. This includes preventing unnecessary duplication of work for students. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 1)&#10;2. The design group is working to ensure greater consistency in delivery by understanding challenges and taking steps to address barriers for consistency. (implied throughout Kirsty Williams AM's statements)&#10;3. Specific resources and professional learning programs are being made available for teachers to ensure they have the skills and confidence to deliver the new qualification in a high-quality manner. This is in line with past practice of providing resources when introducing reformed qualifications. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 1-2)&#10;4. Regional consortia support, WJEC resources, and the national approach to professional learning will specifically address the professional learning needs of those already in the system, ensuring greater consistency and capability in delivering the new qualification. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 3)&#10;5. By working closely with a stakeholder group and a practitioners group, Qualifications Wales can test messages and gather feedback on the qualification's development from those who will be delivering it and potential employers, which contributes to greater consistency in its delivery. (Supporting Materials, point 2)" />
    <edge source="The Welsh baccalaureate can be used as an equivalent to an A-level for some university courses, or may lower the offer requirements if passed at a certain level. Even if not a formal part of the offer, universities value it in the interview and personal statement process, recognizing the skills learned as beneficial for the transition from A-level work to university-type work. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification; Russell Group universities have stated that there is no detriment to Welsh students who undertake the Welsh baccalaureate, as they value the qualification and consider it useful for developing transition skills." target=". First of all, for many of those universities, for many of their courses, they use the Welsh bac as an equivalent to an A-level. If they don't, there are some courses, for instance, where they will lower their offer to gain a place at that university if the Welsh bac is passed at a certain level. So, for instance, rather than maybe offering a Welsh student A, A, B, they would offer a Welsh student A, B, B, plus a Welsh bac, thus giving students two opportunities to gain a place at that university, either with or without their Welsh bac qualification. Even for those universities that don't use the Welsh baccalaureate as a formal part of their offer—and this is the conversation I had again last week with Oxford and Cambridge—they value it as part of a student's personal statement; they value it as part of the interview process in which a student may or may not then be offered a place at that university; and they also recognise that the skills learnt by students whilst undertaking the Welsh baccalaureate are exactly the skills that those students need to make a successful transition from A-level work to university-type work, which, if you can imagine">
