    <edge source="The Welsh baccalaureate can be used as an equivalent to an A-level for some university courses, or may lower the offer requirements if passed at a certain level. Even if not a formal part of the offer, universities value it in the interview and personal statement process, recognizing the skills learned as beneficial for the transition from A-level work to university-type work. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification; Russell Group universities have stated that there is no detriment to Welsh students who undertake the Welsh baccalaureate, as they value the qualification and consider it useful for developing transition skills." target="1. The Welsh baccalaureate can be used as an equivalent to an A-level for some university courses or may lower the offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This is true for many Russell Group universities, which value the qualification and consider it useful for developing transition skills.&#10;2. In terms of consistency, all universities regard the Welsh baccalaureate as a valuable qualification, although they may use it in different ways for offers. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification.&#10;3. A survey and oral evidence presented to the committee suggest that there might be varying perspectives on the Welsh baccalaureate. However, the Cabinet Secretary has reached out to universities directly to determine their views and has found consistent support for the value of the Welsh baccalaureate, with no indication that it disadvantages Welsh students.&#10;4. Qualifications Wales has an individual whose role is to ensure that universities across the United Kingdom understand the value of Welsh qualifications, including the Welsh baccalaureate. This will become increasingly important as English and Welsh qualifications diverge.">
