    <edge source="The Welsh baccalaureate can be used as an equivalent to an A-level for some university courses, or may lower the offer requirements if passed at a certain level. Even if not a formal part of the offer, universities value it in the interview and personal statement process, recognizing the skills learned as beneficial for the transition from A-level work to university-type work. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification; Russell Group universities have stated that there is no detriment to Welsh students who undertake the Welsh baccalaureate, as they value the qualification and consider it useful for developing transition skills." target="1. The advanced level Welsh Baccalaureate is equivalent to an A-level in rigor, as it has been benchmarked against A-levels and assigned a UCAS tariff. It is used by universities for admission purposes similarly to how they use A-level qualifications. The individual project work required by the Welsh Baccalaureate is valued by universities because it teaches a different set of skills compared to traditional syllabi, demanding more from individual students and encouraging independent learning.&#10;&#10;2. There has been some confusion regarding the rigor and equivalency of the Skills Challenge Certificate within the Welsh Baccalaureate, which can be attributed to differences in implementation across schools. Some teachers may not take the bac as seriously as others, leading to inconsistencies in how the qualification is perceived by universities and students.&#10;&#10;3. Kirsty Williams AM clarifies that the Skills Challenge Certificate should not be considered equivalent to an A-level but rather a valuable qualification that develops different skills. It contributes to a broad and balanced curriculum, providing students with diverse learning opportunities and helping them build various knowledge areas and skillsets.&#10;&#10;4. To maintain the ethos of these qualifications in schools, it is crucial to ensure that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand the value and significance of the Welsh Baccalaureate for future success. Strengthening guidance for school leaders on deciding whether a qualification is suitable for their students can help preserve positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities.&#10;&#10;5. Ongoing research, surveys, and open communication between Qualifications Wales and higher education institutions will help address any potential disadvantages faced by Welsh students with the Skills Challenge Certificate, ensuring that institutions across the UK understand its value as Welsh qualifications diverge from English ones.">
