    <edge source="1. The Welsh baccalaureate can be used as an equivalent to an A-level for some university courses or may lower the offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This is true for many Russell Group universities, which value the qualification and consider it useful for developing transition skills.&#10;2. In terms of consistency, all universities regard the Welsh baccalaureate as a valuable qualification, although they may use it in different ways for offers. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification.&#10;3. A survey and oral evidence presented to the committee suggest that there might be varying perspectives on the Welsh baccalaureate. However, the Cabinet Secretary has reached out to universities directly to determine their views and has found consistent support for the value of the Welsh baccalaureate, with no indication that it disadvantages Welsh students.&#10;4. Qualifications Wales has an individual whose role is to ensure that universities across the United Kingdom understand the value of Welsh qualifications, including the Welsh baccalaureate. This will become increasingly important as English and Welsh qualifications diverge." target="1. Flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate: The Welsh Baccalaureate offers flexibility to students by providing different levels (Foundation, National, and Advanced) and pathways (Core, Creative, Enterprise and Commerce, Global Citizenship, and Health and Social Care) based on their interests and career goals. This flexibility allows students to tailor the qualification to their needs and choose subjects that they are passionate about, which can positively influence their perception and value of the program.&#10;&#10;2. Recognition by Russell Group universities: The Welsh Baccalaureate is recognized by many Russell Group universities as equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that may lower offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This recognition increases the value and prestige of the qualification among learners, particularly those who aspire to attend these competitive institutions. Knowing that the Welsh Baccalaureate can help them meet university entrance requirements encourages more students to consider taking it, improving its perception and value at key stage 4 and post-16.&#10;&#10;3. Influence of school leadership: The support and promotion of the Welsh Baccalaureate by school leaders play a significant role in shaping learners' perceptions and valuation of the qualification. When school leaders actively encourage students to participate in the program, create an environment that values and supports its successful completion, and communicate its benefits clearly, learners are more likely to view the Welsh Baccalaureate as a valuable and meaningful educational experience.&#10;&#10;In summary, the flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate, its recognition by Russell Group universities, and the influence of school leadership contribute to its value and perception among learners at key stage 4 or post-16. The qualification's adaptability allows students to personalize their learning experience, while university recognition increases its prestige. Positive endorsement and support from school leaders further enhance learners' perceptions and motivation to engage with the Welsh Baccalaureate.">
