    <edge source="1. The Welsh baccalaureate can be used as an equivalent to an A-level for some university courses or may lower the offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This is true for many Russell Group universities, which value the qualification and consider it useful for developing transition skills.&#10;2. In terms of consistency, all universities regard the Welsh baccalaureate as a valuable qualification, although they may use it in different ways for offers. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification.&#10;3. A survey and oral evidence presented to the committee suggest that there might be varying perspectives on the Welsh baccalaureate. However, the Cabinet Secretary has reached out to universities directly to determine their views and has found consistent support for the value of the Welsh baccalaureate, with no indication that it disadvantages Welsh students.&#10;4. Qualifications Wales has an individual whose role is to ensure that universities across the United Kingdom understand the value of Welsh qualifications, including the Welsh baccalaureate. This will become increasingly important as English and Welsh qualifications diverge." target="1. Introducing a grading system for the Welsh Baccalaureate addresses concerns about its lack of rigor by providing a means of measuring and differentiating students' performance, thereby ensuring that the qualification is taken seriously and valued in its own right. This also enables universities and employers to better assess the achievements of Welsh Baccalaureate students when making offers or recruitment decisions.&#10;2. An independent process benchmarking qualifications helps to establish the credibility and rigor of the Welsh Baccalaureate by comparing it with other qualifications, both within Wales and internationally. This provides assurance that the Welsh Baccalaureate meets appropriate standards and is recognized as a valuable and rigorous qualification, thus enhancing its value and addressing concerns about its perceived lack of rigor.&#10;3. By having a grading system and independent benchmarking process in place, the Welsh Baccalaureate can be more consistently valued and understood by universities and employers across the UK. This ensures that Welsh students are not disadvantaged when applying for further education or jobs, as their qualifications will be recognized and appreciated for their rigor and value.&#10;4. The combination of a grading system and independent benchmarking process can help to dispel negative perceptions about the Welsh Baccalaureate, such as claims that it lacks rigor, is passively marked, or has grades that are inflated. By demonstrating the credibility and value of the qualification, these concerns can be addressed, and the Welsh Baccalaureate can be seen as a genuinely rigorous and valuable educational experience for students in Wales.">
