    <edge source=" and bore da. I was going to ask some general questions about the value of the baccalaureate. Could you give us your views on how the Welsh bac is valued by learners and teachers?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Bore da, Julie, and thank you very much for your question. Firstly, I'd like to begin by saying that I as the Cabinet Secretary value the qualification very much indeed. I believe that it helps ensure that we are able to give our young people in Wales a broad and balanced curriculum, recognising the need to develop knowledge and skills in core subjects but recognising also that the purpose of education is to help prepare our children for further study and the world of work, and I believe that the skills challenge element of the baccalaureate does just that. I meet with young people and teachers all the time who tell me about the positive experiences they have had studying for the Welsh bac, and much of that was evidenced in Qualifications Wales's review into the Welsh baccalaureate. They did focus group work with a representative sample, and many of the learners expressed the fact that they have enjoyed studying for the qualification and have gained a great deal from it. I meet regularly with" target="1. Flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate: The Welsh Baccalaureate offers flexibility to students by providing different levels (Foundation, National, and Advanced) and pathways (Core, Creative, Enterprise and Commerce, Global Citizenship, and Health and Social Care) based on their interests and career goals. This flexibility allows students to tailor the qualification to their needs and choose subjects that they are passionate about, which can positively influence their perception and value of the program.&#10;&#10;2. Recognition by Russell Group universities: The Welsh Baccalaureate is recognized by many Russell Group universities as equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that may lower offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This recognition increases the value and prestige of the qualification among learners, particularly those who aspire to attend these competitive institutions. Knowing that the Welsh Baccalaureate can help them meet university entrance requirements encourages more students to consider taking it, improving its perception and value at key stage 4 and post-16.&#10;&#10;3. Influence of school leadership: The support and promotion of the Welsh Baccalaureate by school leaders play a significant role in shaping learners' perceptions and valuation of the qualification. When school leaders actively encourage students to participate in the program, create an environment that values and supports its successful completion, and communicate its benefits clearly, learners are more likely to view the Welsh Baccalaureate as a valuable and meaningful educational experience.&#10;&#10;In summary, the flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate, its recognition by Russell Group universities, and the influence of school leadership contribute to its value and perception among learners at key stage 4 or post-16. The qualification's adaptability allows students to personalize their learning experience, while university recognition increases its prestige. Positive endorsement and support from school leaders further enhance learners' perceptions and motivation to engage with the Welsh Baccalaureate.">
