    <edge source=" and bore da. I was going to ask some general questions about the value of the baccalaureate. Could you give us your views on how the Welsh bac is valued by learners and teachers?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Bore da, Julie, and thank you very much for your question. Firstly, I'd like to begin by saying that I as the Cabinet Secretary value the qualification very much indeed. I believe that it helps ensure that we are able to give our young people in Wales a broad and balanced curriculum, recognising the need to develop knowledge and skills in core subjects but recognising also that the purpose of education is to help prepare our children for further study and the world of work, and I believe that the skills challenge element of the baccalaureate does just that. I meet with young people and teachers all the time who tell me about the positive experiences they have had studying for the Welsh bac, and much of that was evidenced in Qualifications Wales's review into the Welsh baccalaureate. They did focus group work with a representative sample, and many of the learners expressed the fact that they have enjoyed studying for the qualification and have gained a great deal from it. I meet regularly with" target="1. The Welsh baccalaureate is valued by many universities, including Russell Group universities, as an equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that can lower offer requirements when passed at a certain level. This indicates that the qualification is recognized for its rigor and relevance to undergraduate studies.&#10;2. The skills developed through the Welsh baccalaureate, such as project management, research, and independent learning, are seen as beneficial for the transition from A-level work to university-type work. This suggests that students who have engaged in this type of qualification may be better prepared for the demands of undergraduate studies.&#10;3. There is also evidence to suggest that these skills can be valuable in gaining work experience and internships, as they are highly valued by employers. This means that students who have completed project-based, individual-led, research-based work such as the Welsh baccalaureate or EPQ may have an advantage when it comes to securing work experience and internships during their undergraduate studies.&#10;4. Overall, there is a positive correlation between students who have engaged in project-based, individual-led, research-based work such as the Welsh baccalaureate and EPQ qualifications in the UK, and their potential success in undergraduate studies and gaining work experience.">
