    <edge source="1. Changing the name of the &quot;Welsh Bac&quot; qualification could have an unintended consequence of making the job of developing a better understanding of the qualification even harder. The current name is associated with the qualification's brand, and moving away from it might create confusion and require additional efforts to establish a new identity.&#10;2. Some stakeholders have raised concerns about the rigor of the Welsh Bac qualification, claiming that it lacks rigor and students are spoon-fed. However, the Cabinet Secretary has emphasized that making it a graded qualification has improved its rigor, and there is an independent process benchmarking qualifications to ensure its value.&#10;3. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification, as universities across the UK recognize its value, including Russell Group universities. A Qualifications Wales representative also works to ensure that UK universities understand the value of Welsh qualifications.&#10;4. While there have been some concerns raised about balancing the Welsh Bac with other qualifications and well-being issues, overall, it is valued by many universities as an equivalent to an A-level or a factor in lowering offer requirements for certain courses. Employers were involved in developing the qualification, and many appreciate the skills students acquire through it." target="1. Design group of Qualifications Wales is addressing issues regarding ensuring that the qualification is not too onerous from a teacher workload perspective, particularly in terms of assessment. This includes preventing unnecessary duplication of work for students.&#10;2. A stakeholder group and a practitioners group are working alongside the design group to test messages and gather feedback on the qualification's development from those who will be delivering it and potential employers.&#10;3. Professional learning opportunities are being created for teachers, both through regional consortia support and WJEC resources, as well as via the national approach to professional learning, with specific focus on addressing the professional learning needs of those already in the system.&#10;4. The design group is working to ensure greater consistency in delivery by understanding challenges and taking steps to address barriers for consistency.">
