    <edge source="1. Changing the name of the &quot;Welsh Bac&quot; qualification could have an unintended consequence of making the job of developing a better understanding of the qualification even harder. The current name is associated with the qualification's brand, and moving away from it might create confusion and require additional efforts to establish a new identity.&#10;2. Some stakeholders have raised concerns about the rigor of the Welsh Bac qualification, claiming that it lacks rigor and students are spoon-fed. However, the Cabinet Secretary has emphasized that making it a graded qualification has improved its rigor, and there is an independent process benchmarking qualifications to ensure its value.&#10;3. There is no consensus that Welsh students are disadvantaged by taking this qualification, as universities across the UK recognize its value, including Russell Group universities. A Qualifications Wales representative also works to ensure that UK universities understand the value of Welsh qualifications.&#10;4. While there have been some concerns raised about balancing the Welsh Bac with other qualifications and well-being issues, overall, it is valued by many universities as an equivalent to an A-level or a factor in lowering offer requirements for certain courses. Employers were involved in developing the qualification, and many appreciate the skills students acquire through it." target="1. Introducing a grading system for the Welsh Baccalaureate addresses concerns about its lack of rigor by providing a means of measuring and differentiating students' performance, thereby ensuring that the qualification is taken seriously and valued in its own right. This also enables universities and employers to better assess the achievements of Welsh Baccalaureate students when making offers or recruitment decisions.&#10;2. An independent process benchmarking qualifications helps to establish the credibility and rigor of the Welsh Baccalaureate by comparing it with other qualifications, both within Wales and internationally. This provides assurance that the Welsh Baccalaureate meets appropriate standards and is recognized as a valuable and rigorous qualification, thus enhancing its value and addressing concerns about its perceived lack of rigor.&#10;3. By having a grading system and independent benchmarking process in place, the Welsh Baccalaureate can be more consistently valued and understood by universities and employers across the UK. This ensures that Welsh students are not disadvantaged when applying for further education or jobs, as their qualifications will be recognized and appreciated for their rigor and value.&#10;4. The combination of a grading system and independent benchmarking process can help to dispel negative perceptions about the Welsh Baccalaureate, such as claims that it lacks rigor, is passively marked, or has grades that are inflated. By demonstrating the credibility and value of the qualification, these concerns can be addressed, and the Welsh Baccalaureate can be seen as a genuinely rigorous and valuable educational experience for students in Wales.">
