    <edge source=" think it is a valuable piece of work for Welsh young people to undertake.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: It's great that you've been around listening to learners and what they have said about it. Have you had any negative feedback?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, occasionally, of course, we do have concerns raised with us, and those concerns are similar to the ones that have been raised in the Qualifications Wales review. So, for instance, we sometimes have concerns about how some students balance the Welsh bac with other qualifications they may be taking. Some teachers feed back around the workload issues associated with the Welsh baccalaureate. For some students, there may be concerns about the nature of the Welsh bac and whether that can impact negatively on their well-being. And, obviously, that's why Qualifications Wales have undertaken this piece of work so that we can refine, if necessary, that qualification and how we continue to look at how we ensure my belief that taking the Welsh bac should be the norm for students but also recognising that, in some cases, there needs to be flexibility to ensure that the well-being of the student is not compromised.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;" target="1. Flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate: The Welsh Baccalaureate offers flexibility to students by providing different levels (Foundation, National, and Advanced) and pathways (Core, Creative, Enterprise and Commerce, Global Citizenship, and Health and Social Care) based on their interests and career goals. This flexibility allows students to tailor the qualification to their needs and choose subjects that they are passionate about, which can positively influence their perception and value of the program.&#10;&#10;2. Recognition by Russell Group universities: The Welsh Baccalaureate is recognized by many Russell Group universities as equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that may lower offer requirements if passed at a certain level. This recognition increases the value and prestige of the qualification among learners, particularly those who aspire to attend these competitive institutions. Knowing that the Welsh Baccalaureate can help them meet university entrance requirements encourages more students to consider taking it, improving its perception and value at key stage 4 and post-16.&#10;&#10;3. Influence of school leadership: The support and promotion of the Welsh Baccalaureate by school leaders play a significant role in shaping learners' perceptions and valuation of the qualification. When school leaders actively encourage students to participate in the program, create an environment that values and supports its successful completion, and communicate its benefits clearly, learners are more likely to view the Welsh Baccalaureate as a valuable and meaningful educational experience.&#10;&#10;In summary, the flexibility of the Welsh Baccalaureate, its recognition by Russell Group universities, and the influence of school leadership contribute to its value and perception among learners at key stage 4 or post-16. The qualification's adaptability allows students to personalize their learning experience, while university recognition increases its prestige. Positive endorsement and support from school leaders further enhance learners' perceptions and motivation to engage with the Welsh Baccalaureate.">
