    <edge source=" think it is a valuable piece of work for Welsh young people to undertake.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: It's great that you've been around listening to learners and what they have said about it. Have you had any negative feedback?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, occasionally, of course, we do have concerns raised with us, and those concerns are similar to the ones that have been raised in the Qualifications Wales review. So, for instance, we sometimes have concerns about how some students balance the Welsh bac with other qualifications they may be taking. Some teachers feed back around the workload issues associated with the Welsh baccalaureate. For some students, there may be concerns about the nature of the Welsh bac and whether that can impact negatively on their well-being. And, obviously, that's why Qualifications Wales have undertaken this piece of work so that we can refine, if necessary, that qualification and how we continue to look at how we ensure my belief that taking the Welsh bac should be the norm for students but also recognising that, in some cases, there needs to be flexibility to ensure that the well-being of the student is not compromised.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;" target="1. Ensuring there is support in schools: Kirsty Williams acknowledges that studying A-levels can be a stressful time for young people and emphasizes the need to provide support within schools. This includes ensuring students make informed choices about their qualifications, understanding the importance of quality over quantity in their work, and receiving good information, advice, and guidance from teachers and advisors.&#10;2. Promoting the Welsh Baccalaureate: Kirsty Williams values the Welsh Baccalaureate as contributing to a broad and balanced curriculum that prepares young people for further study and work. She highlights that universities across the UK view the qualification positively, ensuring school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand its value and significance for future success.&#10;3. Flexibility in decision-making: Julie Morgan raises concerns about some teachers feeling undermined when insisting on pupils doing certain qualifications, while facing pressure from parents. She suggests strengthening and clarifying the guidance for school leaders regarding decision-making on suitable qualifications to maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities. This would ensure consistency in approach and prevent confusion.&#10;4. Addressing concerns about well-being: Kirsty Williams acknowledges that there are concerns about how some students balance the Welsh Bac with other qualifications, workload issues associated with it, and its potential impact on their well-being. To address these concerns, Qualifications Wales has undertaken a review to refine the Welsh baccalaureate and ensure that taking the qualification is the norm for students while being flexible to protect students' well-being when necessary.&#10;&#10;In summary, measures being put in place to help young people deal with added pressures and stress include providing support within schools, promoting high-value qualifications like the Welsh Baccalaureate, ensuring consistent decision-making on suitable qualifications, and addressing concerns related to well-being and workload.">
