    <edge source="1. The design group of Qualifications Wales is addressing issues regarding ensuring that the new qualification is not too onerous from a teacher workload perspective, particularly in terms of assessment. This includes preventing unnecessary duplication of work for students. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 1)&#10;2. Specific resources and professional learning programs are being made available for teachers to ensure they have the skills and confidence to deliver the new qualification in a high-quality manner. This is in line with past practice of providing resources when introducing reformed qualifications. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 1-2)&#10;3. There will be opportunities via regional consortia for support in teaching the qualification, and the WJEC has resources and support available. As part of the national approach to professional learning, there will be specific focus on addressing the professional learning needs of those already in the system. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 3)&#10;4. ITE reforms are primarily aimed at preparing teachers for 'Successful Futures' and delivering the Welsh baccalaureate with the required pedagogical principles. Ensuring teachers have these skills is a part of the accreditation process for new ITE providers. (Kirsty Williams AM, point 4)&#10;5. The design group will continue to refine the qualification and ensure consistency in delivery by understanding challenges and taking steps to address barriers for consistency. (implied throughout Kirsty Williams AM's statements)" target="1. The Welsh government plans to ensure consistent support and enthusiasm for the Welsh Baccalaureate (the &quot;bac&quot;) from leaders by addressing concerns about teacher workload. A design group of Qualifications Wales is working on ensuring that the qualification is not too burdensome in terms of assessment, aiming to prevent unnecessary duplication of work for both teachers and students.&#10;2. They will provide specific resources and professional learning programs for teachers to ensure they have the necessary skills and confidence to deliver the new qualification effectively. This initiative aligns with past practices of offering support when introducing reformed qualifications.&#10;3. Opportunities for regional consortia support and WJEC resources will be available, as well as a national approach to professional learning focused on addressing the professional learning needs of those already in the system.&#10;4. The government is also reforming Initial Teacher Education (ITE) to prepare teachers for 'Successful Futures' and delivering the Welsh baccalaureate with the required pedagogical principles. Ensuring teachers have these skills is part of the accreditation process for new ITE providers.&#10;5. By addressing these concerns and creating an enabling environment through professional learning opportunities, the Welsh government aims to foster consistency in delivering the qualification and maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities.">
