    <edge source="&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. The next questions are from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: This is about the wider impact of studying the Welsh bac on other curriculum subjects and education provision, and we've had representations in that it is causing some concerns. So, do you have any concerns about the effect that the Welsh bac may be having on wider education provisions, such as the narrowing of the curriculum at key stage 4?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: No. Obviously, schools are responsible for planning their local curriculum offer, and that needs to meet the needs of their learners, and it also needs to meet the needs of the Learning and Skills (Wales) Measure 2009. So, there should be a wide variety of choices available. I believe that the skills challenge certificate actually does ensure that there is a broad curriculum and that children are exposed to different learning opportunities. And so, rather than narrowing it, I believe the Welsh bac helps us to make sure that there is an expansive curriculum, and that lots of different issues are explored in the skills challenge certificate that ensure not just academic skills are developed, but," target="1. The varying opinions regarding the rigor and equivalency of the Skills Challenge Certificate compared to traditional A-level qualifications can be attributed to differences in understanding and implementation of the Welsh Baccalaureate across schools. Some teachers may not be taking the bac as seriously as others, which could lead to inconsistencies in how the qualification is perceived by universities and students.&#10;2. Kirsty Williams AM emphasizes that the Skills Challenge Certificate should not be held up as equivalent to an A-level, but rather viewed as a qualification that develops different skills. It is important to acknowledge these differences and understand that the Welsh Baccalaureate contributes to a broad and balanced curriculum, exposing students to various learning opportunities and helping them develop a wider range of knowledge and skills.&#10;3. To uphold the ethos and skills associated with these qualifications in schools, there should be continued efforts to ensure that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand the value and significance of the Welsh Baccalaureate for future success. Strengthening and clarifying guidance for school leaders regarding decision-making on whether a qualification is suitable for students can help maintain positive relationships between teachers, parents, and educational authorities.&#10;4. Ongoing research, surveys, and open communication between Qualifications Wales and higher education institutions can help address any potential disadvantages faced by Welsh students with the Skills Challenge Certificate, ensuring that institutions across the UK understand its value as Welsh qualifications diverge from English ones.">
