    <edge source="1. The Welsh baccalaureate is valued by many universities, including Russell Group universities, as an equivalent to an A-level or as a qualification that can lower offer requirements when passed at a certain level. This indicates that the qualification is recognized for its rigor and relevance to undergraduate studies.&#10;2. The skills developed through the Welsh baccalaureate, such as project management, research, and independent learning, are seen as beneficial for the transition from A-level work to university-type work. This suggests that students who have engaged in this type of qualification may be better prepared for the demands of undergraduate studies.&#10;3. There is also evidence to suggest that these skills can be valuable in gaining work experience and internships, as they are highly valued by employers. This means that students who have completed project-based, individual-led, research-based work such as the Welsh baccalaureate or EPQ may have an advantage when it comes to securing work experience and internships during their undergraduate studies.&#10;4. Overall, there is a positive correlation between students who have engaged in project-based, individual-led, research-based work such as the Welsh baccalaureate and EPQ qualifications in the UK, and their potential success in undergraduate studies and gaining work experience." target=" who have been involved in project-based work—and, of course, that's not just the Welsh baccalaureate, that would be the EPQ, which is a qualification that is rapidly gaining traction in England. That is an extended project—research based—qualification, very similar to the individual project element of the Welsh baccalaureate. The EPQ in England is seen as a qualification taken by more able and talented students, and what we see in some of the research that is coming forward is that those students who have engaged in that type of work, project-based work, individual-led, research-based work—those skills are the skills that are really attuned to the nature of university-type work. Therefore, that is valued by universities and there is some indication to say that there is a correlation between the students who have undertaken that work and their potential success at undergraduate level. They also tell me that there is a link between, for instance, being able then to use those skills to gain work experience, placements and internships in the private sector and in the world of work, because, as I said, those types of skills are really, really valuable and therefore that's why they value the qualification.&#10;Spe">
