    <edge source="The Cabinet Secretary for Education, Kirsty Williams AM, values the Welsh Baccalaureate highly and believes it contributes to a broad and balanced curriculum that prepares young people for further study and work. She has consistently received support from universities across the United Kingdom, who view the qualification as valuable and not disadvantageous to Welsh students. Williams emphasizes the importance of ensuring that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand the value and significance of the Welsh Baccalaureate for future success." target="The significant change made to the Skills Challenge Certificate in 2015 was that it shifted from a 'yes'/'no' qualification to a graded one. This change has led to an improvement in how some universities regard it, as they previously held it in less regard when it was not a graded qualification. The new grading system has resulted in more universities recognizing the value of the Skills Challenge Certificate and considering it useful for developing a specific set of skills that help students transition into higher education. This shift has contributed to ensuring that Welsh students undertaking this qualification are not at any detriment, and it is valued by Russell Group universities and others across the UK.">
