    <edge source=" As you know, mental health and the emotional health of our children and young people is a very core issue for this committee, and Estyn have said that studying the skills challenge certificate alongside three or four A-levels is a significant factor in causing stress for some young people. How do you respond to that?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, I would be the first to acknowledge that studying A-levels can be a very stressful time. That's because students, rightly, regard those qualifications as high stakes and as having a profound effect on the opportunities for the rest of their lives. So, the mere fact of studying A-levels can be a really stressful time for students because they understand how important they are, and students want to do well and they want to be able to move on to the next stage, either of work or of university. We also know—and Estyn reflects this—that students are also often trying to combine that with part-time jobs. These students are of an age when they want to be out and about and earning some of their own money and being a bit more independent. So, that adds added pressure to them. So, undoubtedly, this is a stressful time in young people's lives and we" target="1. The importance and high stakes associated with A-level qualifications: Kirsty Williams AM recognizes that the pressure to perform well in A-levels can be a significant source of stress for students, as they understand the profound impact these qualifications have on their future opportunities for work or university education.&#10;&#10;2. Combining studies with part-time jobs: Many students trying to balance A-levels with part-time jobs experience added pressure and stress. This is especially true for young people who want to be financially independent and earn their own money.&#10;&#10;3. Desire for social activities and independence: The committee mentioned that this stage of life is a time when young people want to be out and about, which can contribute to the stress they experience during their A-level studies. Kirsty Williams AM acknowledges this need for social interaction and independence among students.&#10;&#10;4. Inadequate understanding and implementation of the Welsh Baccalaureate: While not directly stated in the transcript, it is implied that inconsistencies in how the Welsh Baccalaureate (including the Skills Challenge Certificate) is perceived and implemented across schools may exacerbate students' stress levels. Ensuring that school leaders, teachers, parents, and students understand its value and significance can help alleviate some of this pressure.">
