    <edge source="1. The question asks whether there are plans to pause the universal roll-out of the Welsh Baccalaureate, considering that not all schools are currently ready to deliver it to a high standard. From the transcript, it is clear that Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, does not intend to pause the roll-out. She emphasizes the importance of investing in professional learning to ensure that all schools can deliver the qualification well, rather than stopping the opportunity for students to study it." target="1. By &quot;universal adoption&quot; of the Welsh Baccalaureate, Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, means that all institutions should be in a position to deliver the qualification. She believes it should be an entitlement for all Welsh students to have access to and study this qualification, with the aim of it becoming the norm for students to take the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;2. While emphasizing the importance of universal adoption, Kirsty Williams AM also recognizes exceptions to the alignment of the Welsh Baccalaureate with individual students' well-being. She acknowledges that there may be specific cases where taking the Welsh Baccalaureate might not be suitable for a student due to valid reasons related to their well-being. In such situations, she believes flexibility should be allowed, and there should be evidence justifying why the decision was taken for the student not to pursue the qualification.">
